content.text:
how can we modify the following c++ code to print out the level of each node in the binary tree, in addition to its value?
struct node {
int val;
node* left;
node* right;
node(int x) : val(x), left(null), right(null) {}
};
void printtree(node* root) {
if (root == null) return;
cout << root->val << " ";
printtree(root->left);
printtree(root->right);

to print out the level of each node in the binary tree, you can add an additional parameter to the `printtree` function to keep track of the current level. here's the modified code:
```
void printtree(node* root, int level = 0) {
if (root == null) return;
cout << root->val << " (level " << level << ")" << endl;
printtree(root->left, level + 1);
printtree(root->right, level + 1);
}
```
with this modification, the `printtree` function now takes an additional `level` parameter, which is initially set to 0. when we print out the value of a node, we also print out its level by appending " (level x)" to the output, where x is the current level. we then recursively call `printtree` on the left and right subtrees with `level + 1` to print out the levels of their nodes.

